title: Uber 180 Redesign -- No Supports Needed, VTX + Cam Mounts, Motor Guards

description.text:
This is a redesign to add features to the Uber and make it more printable.

Mid:

Modifies the design for print-ability. No support is necessary. Original was hard to print and required support. It has been modified to have the cross spars for the battery strap at the bottom, so they can print right on your bed. The bottom has also been flattened, as the original had basically no surface area. Please let me know how these work for you.

Top:

Adds an SMA connection hole to the top plate of the Uber 180. Needed to protect your vtx and also a good way to mount the vtx without any other fasteners. Also removed rounded corners to make printing easier.

Top With Cam Mount:

Added a camera mounting hole for standard size FPV cams. It is angled at 40 or 30 deg, depending which file you choose. Please let me know if you want a different angle, or a different camera size. I tried to make it user configurable, but it just wasn't possible.

Motor Mount:

Added a small guard piece to the motor mount. Should protect the motors from most impacts from the side. They fit rs2205s and should fit any 220x motor.

Notes

Materials

Nylon 910 is the recommended material. Well printed PLA might be strong enough for some pieces some of the time, but Nylon is really the only material strong enough to make this frame viable.

Printing

Go slow and hot to insure good bonding. Thin layers are recommended for strength, depending on your material.

Assembly

You can refer to the original uber180(shown as the remix on this page) for cut lengths and assembly instructions.

I chose to dye my nylon orange with RIT dye.

I lightly glued motor mounts to tubes using superglue. Using less glue means you might actually be able to get it apart later.

Hardware: I used 20mm m3 button head screws and 10mm nylon standoffs with standard 35mm aluminum standoffs on top, from a ZMR kit. I recommend metal screws and standoffs all the way up for structure. I had some nylon screws and they sheared off on impact.

description.text:
I really liked oscahie's cooling fan design and used one for a long time but eventually wanted to use a radial fan. This was cobbled together in Tinkercad. The fan is a 50mm radial fan. If I can find the actual one I bought, I'll post a link later.

I had this mounted in my Da Vinci 1.0, so I can vouch that it works. I just had to remove it while I was refitting the printer with Ramps 1.4, E3D Titan, Octopi, and some other upgrades.

One thing about printing this - you'll notice that the orientation of the stl is odd. This is because I wanted the layer lines to go a certain way. It was printed with supports that I generated in Simplify3D, which has always done a great job on supports for me (easy to configure and to remove). I printed it in PETG at .3 layer height and it worked great. oscahie's original design can be printed without support, but I couldn't find a way to do that with this one. Feel free to experiment with it!

(Dremel Filament, Aspeteck, and WYZ brand). If someone has something that needs to be a little different, do not hesitate to let me know, and I will gladly create one for you.

It is also my understanding that this will work well with the Flashforge Dreamer, but I don't have one, so I cannot attest to that.

Anyway, I set the prints on more of a standard setting but to print a bit faster. I'm impatient that way. Needed to find some (8) M3 machine screws with (8) nuts/ (16) washers, etc. I tend to "over engineer" but the idea is to replace the existing vent (simple clip out) with a sandwich style plate, that won't change anything about your existing printer. No holes to drill, etc. Model is metric, so scale accordingly. The main plate should be 119mm x 139mm max.

The photos show pretty good on how to assemble the unit. Just set it all up and run the filament through the back grate of the printer and you are good to go. If you have any questions though, let me know. I will be happy to answer them.

Thanks! Enjoy!

Oh - I also included a bonus file - it's a little "chute" to run the filament from the side of the printer to the back, but I didn't like it much, so I don't use it. Maybe someone could come up with a better way of doing that. :)

Uploaded Version 2 slider brackets with slots and screw holes to clamp rods in place (like the original Smartfriendz pieces). I noticed my X-axis sagged slightly under the tension of the belts without these.

Also uploaded templates to use to drill the holes for mounting the corner pieces. This helps align the holes properly. These are placed on the outside of the box. These will ONLY WORK WITH 1/2 INCH WOOD.

Here is my pseudo-SmartrapCore design. I made some design changes inspired by the X3D CoreXY printer (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:730199) so that the corner brackets don't hang over the edges.

This design is for 8 mm rods.

The corner brackets mount with three M3 screws and nuts each. Surprisingly, they are quite sturdy and don't budge at all. Make sure to tighten them well (use nylon lock nuts).

FYI: I would recommend using the y-axis sliders that I uploaded instead of the official ones. I am not sure the belts will align properly otherwise.

I've uploaded both STL and STEP files. I had to put very large tolerances on the 8mm holes (8.2 mm) because of the poor dimensional accuracy of my old printer. If you are having trouble editing the STEP files, let me know and I can reupload part files with tighter tolerances!

This super simple design of a toilet roll holder is a screw-no-glue design for flat pack shipping and easy assembly. The removable part has some magnets to snap in place. I did resign on a rounded part in favor of a more simple machining process.

The build was done on a desktop cnc-machine from Stepcraft from 12.5 mm birch plywood using a spiral-toothed 3 mm flute. The surface got some clear spray-paint to intensify the wood structure and to make it water-resistant.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs.

description.text: This holder is to IKEA's LED lighting to kitchen cabinets, I made them when we had to replace our old halogen light fixtures to IKEA's new LED. It turned out that the old hole was too small for these new, so it could not just push them up in the old hole. irritated by this, I thought that then you have to screw them on the cabinet ceiling. But surprised again, it turns out that the screw holes in the new armature is tighter than the hole is. The hole is in this case too large. So what do you make of this mistake from IKEA. Well you're happily owner of a 3D printer. so it was just to sit at the computer and make a suitable adapter. The results presented here work perfectly, made for IKEA's cabinets 16mm thick shelves.

title: Indoor Micro FPV Copter

description.text:
A micro FPV quad copter based on the Scisky brushed flight controller board. Perfect for beginner FPV and indoor practice, this board will run Cleanflight allowing you to configure it to your hearts content.

The camera is easily removable, just unplug it and remove the elastic band holding it on. Then you can also practice your acro tricks indoors with a small, light copter that wont do much damage to things it hits, or itself when you crash.

Design considerations:

  • All electronics can be removed without desoldering if you break the frame (though so far it is proving to be fairly robust)
  • Camera can be quickly and easily removed
  • Camera can be either held on with a zip tie, or an elastic band which means that it a crash it just gets dislodged, rather than damaging the antenna.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa I3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm

Notes:

Optimized for a 0.4mm nozzle.

You'll need:

  • Scisky Brushed Flight Controller: http://www.radioc.co.uk/Micro-scisky-32bit-brushed-fc-p/3119.htm
  • Motors: http://www.dronejunkie.co.uk/product/cl-0820-coreless-motor/
  • Battery: http://www.hobbyking.com/hobbyking/store/uh_viewitem.asp?idproduct=37566
  • Camera: http://www.banggood.com/Eachine-EF-01-AIO-5_8G-40CH-25MW-VTX-800TVL-13-Cmos-FPV-Camera-p-1064301.html
  • Some Hubsan propellers

Optionally (if you have a Spektrum transmitter that doesn't support DSM2 - i.e. a European one):

  • Lemon RX receiver: http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/Lemon-RX-DSMX-Satellite-Receiver-UK-Same-Day-Shipping-Spektrum-Compatible-/262538941725

There is a good guide to set up here: http://community.micro-motor-warehouse.com/t/how-to-set-up-scisky-fc-step-by-step/1224

The motors connect to the closest motor connection on the board, be sure to get the motor rotations correct based on the colour of their wires. You should be able to wrap the wires around the arms before inserting the motors into the motor holders. You might want to add a small blob of glue to stop the motors sliding up and down in their mounts.

As I discovered if you are in the EU and have a recent Spektrum DSMX/DSM2 transmitter then it wont bind with this flight controller because DSM2 has been "banned" in Europe so all the DSMX/DSM2 transmitters are actually just DSMX. The Scisky board however is DSM2 only and so wont bind.

To overcome this get a Lemon RX DSMX satellite from the link above, remove the case an connect it to your flight controller board as per the instructions in this thread http://community.micro-motor-warehouse.com/t/fc-scisky-dsmx-satellite-mod/522

The key to getting the Lemon RX to bind is to use the Cleanflight cli to "set spektrum_sat_bind = 9" (or maybe 7, I forget which worked for me). Details in the above forum post.

I used some liquid electrical tape to secure the 3.3V connection on the main board. Hot glue would also work well. I then wrapped mine in heatshrink to stop it from shorting with anything on the main flight controller board.

Lemon RX mod connected to Serial connector and taking power from a pad on the board. Lemon RX receiver wrapped in heat shrink and packed on top of the Scisky flight controller board. The two antenna poke out of the front and the back of the copter.

These are a collection of connections to join pipes to make garden net supports using press cleaning pipes from a printing press.
I have a supply of pipes used at work and collected them before being dumped I needed a way to join them up.

After a number of designs I came up with a pintable design which could be used, I printed in both PLA and ABS and printed at infil from 70% to 90% to make them very strong. I printed PLA on glass no raft and infil set to 70% using strong glue sticks to hold it to the table. I made the bottoms of the joints flat to enable them to stick better. However when switching to ABS versions I used a raft to prevent warping and help hold them to the table. I did not use my active fan during printing. and printed these on a CTC printer with upgraded extruders. which enabled better filerment feeding when using ABS. The door file can have a metal rod inserted to make hinges or hinge files can be merged ontop by adding and positioning them in place like the film the fly when the man ends up with the head of a fly and the fly a head of a man. in short you can merge files together and print one item .
I have tried dropping a hinge file ontop sink the hinge below the first item to merge the join.

My net will look like a polytunnel but with a net so I guess this would also make a ploy tunnel. The size of my pipes I am using is 18mm inner size and 24mm outer size. You could use ony size to make them fit your pipes I found if you use masking tape and paper on your print bed/table with the raft off you can print a couples of layers of print and remove the paper to check the size with out having to print a whole piece. just turn it on its end to print the pipe shape first and scale to your own water or other type of pipes. I have made some joints with holes if I need cross supports to prevent wind damage. I could just cut the pipe and add these in where needed also made some tab links to help join to wood these are just an example of some you could make yourself and could be used for growning beds.
Happy gardening and printing.
If you only want low nets then drop the infil down to 10% which make quicker but weaker joints. I did try printing with holes down the joints to save filerment but found the nozzles where knocking them off the bed with warping.
The flat bottoms make them more printable than my early round bottom versions which needed support on .

Added two sketchup design files for you to alter to you own design.

Printed using a upgraded CTC printer with metal version extruders and printed onto glass with strong glue sticks.
I printed PLA direct on the glass and it worked but fould it better to use a raft. ABS version do need the rafts and are prone to some warping yet they still work fine, I printed 70% to 90% to make them stronger. lower infil produces them faster and weaker yet ok for low ground nets. Some of these files do take upto and over three hours to print.
I have had my printer running 24 hours some days to produce the amount I need and I have a number of 4mm plain glass sheets,
which I have found work ok. During this run I only renew the glue stick where the printed item sits or where the glue stick layer is missing. if you print the same item many times just fill the glue stick spaces where lifted or missing saves time and glue stick.
You could scale your joint bolts to match the pipe your have,
I used Sketchup to make the files. I started by making a six sided cube with the shape of the inserts on all sides then pulled them out to 25mm size and back deleted the insert shape off the cube this means you can make many shapes from one cube to match your project. My eary versions where weaker and broke so I set about printing a quicker and stroner version and found flat bottom joins made it a lot better to print and did not effect the joining of the pipes. I also needed to improve any after work on the printed product and found these worked straight off the printer without any work to them.the reduced cube size help to make them stronger my larger cubed versions where weak and broke off the face of the cube the tube over laps the cube but I dont mind.
The door catch I suggest printing lower infil I have also made catch 1 and 2 files use support and rafts the full catch diplayed seven hours to print with higer infil and I made two files to help to build it better. I small lock and chain or hook can be used to hold it closed or just a simple chain and peg.
I have tried to make all sorts of diffrent shapes to make diffrent things around the garden.

the flats on the bottom save time with printing and help to stay on the glass better while printing.

I might be down to the layers snapping. but my design was seven foot high.

How I designed this is the heart of the lesson. I took a toy found in my classroom and duplicated a piece of the puzzle using Tinkercad design software. I then printed it and used it to replace the piece I duplicated.

Reverse Engineering Lesson Students will learn about reverse engineering, by taking a piece of an object and recreating it in 3D software. If they are successful, they can use their part as a replacement for the original. Objectives Define reverse engineering as the process of disassembly and careful analysis with the goal of duplicating or improving a device or component.
Demonstrate the process of reverse engineering using a given object or component and suggest areas of improvement. Skills Learned Analyze data from tests to determine similarities and differences among several design solutions to identify the best characteristics of each that can be combined into a new solution to better meet the criteria for success. (Grades 6 - 8) Develop a model to generate data for iterative testing and modification of a proposed object, tool, or process such that an optimal design can be achieved. (Grades 6 - 8) Math
Grades 6–8 students should– understand both metric and customary systems of measurement; understand relationships among units and convert from one unit to another within the same system; understand, select, and use units of appropriate size and type to measure angles, perimeter, area, surface area, and volume.
Grades 9–12 students should– make decisions about units and scales that are appropriate for problem situations involving measurement

The instructor begins by describing the reverse engineering process. Each student group will be assigned a part of an object (in my case it was a piece of a wooden puzzle). Students will measure their part and draw it in three views on the engineering design paper. (Example of design drawing in "files") After instructor approval of the design, students will then use 3D design software to create a printable part. The parts will be printed, and tested against the original part. Students are successful if their part goes back into the original object and performs the same or better than the original part. Day 1 Explain the reverse engineering process, and why it is necessary. This will be a good time to discuss what measurement units would be best to use (In Tinkercad, metric (mm) is the default) Students could begin to disassemble their given object to prepare for the design process. Day 2 Students measure their assigned part and sketch it out on paper. showing all dimensions. They will need to understand that they will need to show three views - Front, Top and Side, in order to get the complete 3D structure. Day 3-4 Depending on the complexity of the part - my part took 5 minutes to design.
Printing time is dependent on the number of parts printed, capacity and speed of printer.

• Toys or objects that can be disassembled (and reassembled) - one for each group.
  • 3D design software with accounts for all students
  • Handout (in "files")
  • Students will need something to measure their parts. Calipers and Rulers are recommended.
3-4 Days

• Students will be assessed on the quality of their drawn design (are there 3 views?, Do they line up? Is all information necessary included?)

  • Students will also have to show that their reverse-engineered part works as well or better than the original part.
http://www.teachengineering.org/activities/view/cub_engineering_in_reverse

description.text:
The GM (Delphi) key fob is apparently weak around the ring attachment hole. I fixed up my coworker's fob with this bit.

Here is a helpful link with pictures: GM Key Fob Remote Control Battery Replacement Guide

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

No

Resolution:

0.10 mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

This thing is really small. Print a few at once (or alongside other things) so the plastic has time to cool between layers.

Separate the two halves of the key fob. Cut or grind off the top of the front half to leave a flat surface the same size as the mating surface of this thing. See photos. Sand both surfaces lightly and super glue together. I used a 2 mm thick metal plate to support the thing and align it with the fob.

You could also put one of these on the back side for more robustness. That would eliminate the opening notch, which isn't terribly important anyway.
